                {
                        "heading": "The Hyksos Period and Semitic Rule in Egypt",
                        "body": "The Hyksos (Egyptian heqa khasut, 'rulers of foreign lands') were Semitic peoples who controlled Lower Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period (c. 1650–1550 BC). Their capital at Avaris (Tell el-Dab'a) in the eastern Nile Delta is the region later called Goshen. Archaeological excavations by Manfred Bietak have revealed a Semitic settlement with Canaanite-style houses, burials with weapons, and a palace complex with a tomb containing a seated statue of a Semitic official in a multicolored garment. While direct identification with Joseph remains debated, the cultural context is undeniable: Semitic peoples held high office in Egypt during precisely this period. A Hebrew vizier would have been unremarkable under Hyksos rule."
                },
                {
                        "heading": "Egyptian Dream Interpretation and the Chartummim",
                        "body": "Dream interpretation (oneiromancy) was a formal discipline in ancient Egypt. The Chester Beatty Papyrus III (c. 1275 BC, but copying older material) is a dream manual categorizing dreams as favorable or unfavorable and providing interpretive keys. The chartummim who failed to interpret Pharaoh's dreams (Genesis 41:8) were lector-priests trained in reading sacred texts and performing ritual interpretation. The word chartummim may derive from the Egyptian hery-tp ('chief, one who is over'), referring to their senior priestly status. Joseph's claim that interpretation belongs to God (Elohim), not to human technique, represents a fundamental theological challenge to the Egyptian system: divine revelation trumps institutional knowledge."
                },
